---
import { u } from '../../utils/url';
import Callout from '../../components/blog/Callout.astro';
---

<p>
  Both clamp meters and multimeters measure electrical quantities — but they work on fundamentally different principles, suit different situations, and are not interchangeable. Understanding the difference will save you money, time, and potentially a blown fuse.
</p>

<!-- ── CORE DIFFERENCE ── -->
<h2 id="core-difference">The Core Difference</h2>

<!-- Measurement method comparison -->
<div class="my-8 rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white overflow-hidden">
  <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 divide-y sm:divide-y-0 sm:divide-x divide-gray-100">
    <!-- Multimeter -->
    <div class="p-6">
      <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <span class="inline-block bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest px-3 py-1 rounded-full border border-blue-200 mb-3">Multimeter</span>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 200 140" class="w-full max-w-xs mx-auto" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <!-- Source -->
          <rect x="10" y="55" width="30" height="30" rx="5" fill="#EFF6FF" stroke="#3B82F6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="25" y="68" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#3B82F6" font-family="monospace">LOAD</text>
          <text x="25" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#3B82F6" font-family="monospace">230V</text>
          <!-- Wire top, broken for meter -->
          <line x1="40" y1="62" x2="75" y2="62" stroke="#1E40AF" stroke-width="2"/>
          <!-- Meter in series -->
          <rect x="75" y="48" width="50" height="28" rx="6" fill="#DBEAFE" stroke="#3B82F6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="100" y="63" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-weight="700" fill="#1D4ED8" font-family="monospace">A</text>
          <text x="100" y="73" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#3B82F6" font-family="sans-serif">in-series</text>
          <!-- Wire continues -->
          <line x1="125" y1="62" x2="160" y2="62" stroke="#1E40AF" stroke-width="2"/>
          <!-- Load right -->
          <rect x="160" y="55" width="30" height="30" rx="5" fill="#EFF6FF" stroke="#3B82F6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="175" y="68" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#3B82F6" font-family="monospace">LOAD</text>
          <text x="175" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#3B82F6" font-family="monospace">DEVICE</text>
          <!-- Return wire bottom -->
          <line x1="40" y1="78" x2="160" y2="78" stroke="#1E40AF" stroke-width="2"/>
          <!-- Break marks -->
          <line x1="62" y1="54" x2="78" y2="70" stroke="#E0252E" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="122" y1="54" x2="138" y2="70" stroke="#E0252E" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <!-- Label -->
          <text x="100" y="115" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#E0252E" font-family="sans-serif">Circuit must be BROKEN</text>
          <text x="100" y="128" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#E0252E" font-family="sans-serif">to insert the meter</text>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The multimeter's current input is placed <strong>in series</strong> with the load. You must physically cut the circuit, insert the meter, take the reading, then restore the circuit.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Clamp meter -->
    <div class="p-6">
      <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <span class="inline-block bg-red-100 text-red-700 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest px-3 py-1 rounded-full border border-red-200 mb-3">Clamp Meter</span>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 200 140" class="w-full max-w-xs mx-auto" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <!-- Source left -->
          <rect x="10" y="55" width="30" height="30" rx="5" fill="#FEF2F2" stroke="#E0252E" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="25" y="68" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#E0252E" font-family="monospace">LOAD</text>
          <text x="25" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#E0252E" font-family="monospace">230V</text>
          <!-- Wire straight through -->
          <line x1="40" y1="62" x2="160" y2="62" stroke="#F59E0B" stroke-width="4"/>
          <!-- Clamp jaw around wire -->
          <path d="M85,40 Q70,40 70,62 Q70,84 85,84 L85,72 Q80,72 80,62 Q80,52 85,52 Z" fill="#E0252E" stroke="#0D1B2A" stroke-width="1"/>
          <path d="M115,40 Q130,40 130,62 Q130,84 115,84 L115,72 Q120,72 120,62 Q120,52 115,52 Z" fill="#E0252E" stroke="#0D1B2A" stroke-width="1"/>
          <!-- Clamp body (meter) -->
          <rect x="85" y="84" width="30" height="40" rx="5" fill="#1B3A5B" stroke="#0D1B2A" stroke-width="1"/>
          <rect x="89" y="88" width="22" height="12" rx="3" fill="#0D1B2A"/>
          <text x="100" y="97" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#00FF88" font-family="monospace">8.4 A</text>
          <!-- Load right -->
          <rect x="160" y="55" width="30" height="30" rx="5" fill="#FEF2F2" stroke="#E0252E" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="175" y="68" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#E0252E" font-family="monospace">LOAD</text>
          <text x="175" y="78" text-anchor="middle" font-size="7" fill="#E0252E" font-family="monospace">DEVICE</text>
          <!-- Return wire bottom -->
          <line x1="40" y1="78" x2="160" y2="78" stroke="#F59E0B" stroke-width="2.5"/>
          <!-- Label -->
          <text x="100" y="133" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" fill="#22C55E" font-family="sans-serif">No circuit break needed</text>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The clamp jaw wraps around the conductor and detects current <strong>magnetically</strong> — zero contact with the live conductor. The circuit stays intact throughout.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── COMPARISON TABLE ── -->
<h2 id="comparison">Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>

<div class="my-8 rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
  <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
    <thead>
      <tr class="bg-[#0D1B2A]">
        <th class="text-left px-5 py-4 text-[#94a3b8] font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest w-[35%]">Feature</th>
        <th class="text-center px-4 py-4 text-blue-300 font-bold">Multimeter</th>
        <th class="text-center px-4 py-4 text-red-300 font-bold">Clamp Meter</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {[
        { feature:'Current measurement', dmm:'In-series via shunt resistor', clamp:'Non-contact via jaw (induction / Hall)', winner:'—' },
        { feature:'Circuit break required for current', dmm:'Yes ✕', clamp:'No ✓', winner:'clamp' },
        { feature:'Max current range (typical)', dmm:'10–20 A', clamp:'400–1000 A or more', winner:'clamp' },
        { feature:'Low current accuracy (< 1 A)', dmm:'Excellent (mA resolution)', clamp:'Poor — field too weak to read', winner:'dmm' },
        { feature:'Voltage measurement', dmm:'Excellent — primary function', clamp:'Available via probes, secondary', winner:'dmm' },
        { feature:'Resistance / continuity', dmm:'Excellent, 0.1% accuracy', clamp:'Available, coarser (~1%)', winner:'dmm' },
        { feature:'Component testing (diode, cap)', dmm:'Yes ✓', clamp:'Rarely ✕', winner:'dmm' },
        { feature:'Safety around live conductors', dmm:'Higher risk (probes touch conductor)', clamp:'Lower risk (jaw around insulation)', winner:'clamp' },
        { feature:'Inrush / peak current capture', dmm:'No ✕', clamp:'Yes — dedicated function ✓', winner:'clamp' },
        { feature:'DC current measurement', dmm:'Yes ✓', clamp:'Only Hall Effect models', winner:'dmm' },
        { feature:'Form factor', dmm:'Compact, pocket-sized', clamp:'Larger — jaw adds bulk', winner:'dmm' },
      ].map((row, i) => (
        <tr class={i % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-white' : 'bg-gray-50'}>
          <td class="px-5 py-3 text-[#0D1B2A] font-medium border-b border-gray-100 text-xs">{row.feature}</td>
          <td class={`px-4 py-3 text-center text-xs border-b border-gray-100 ${row.winner === 'dmm' ? 'bg-blue-50 text-blue-800 font-semibold' : 'text-gray-600'}`}>{row.dmm}</td>
          <td class={`px-4 py-3 text-center text-xs border-b border-gray-100 ${row.winner === 'clamp' ? 'bg-red-50 text-red-800 font-semibold' : 'text-gray-600'}`}>{row.clamp}</td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <div class="flex gap-4 px-5 py-3 bg-gray-50 border-t border-gray-200 text-xs text-gray-500">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded bg-blue-100 border border-blue-300"></span>Multimeter wins</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded bg-red-100 border border-red-300"></span>Clamp meter wins</span>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── WHEN MULTIMETER ── -->
<h2 id="choose-multimeter">When to Choose a Multimeter</h2>

<div class="my-6 space-y-2">
  {[
    { icon:'🔬', use:'Diagnosing electronic circuits', why:'The mA current range and component test functions (diode, capacitance, temperature) are things a clamp meter simply cannot do.' },
    { icon:'〰️', use:'Low current measurements (< 1 A)', why:'Magnetic fields below 1 A are too weak for most clamp jaws to read accurately. A multimeter in series handles this comfortably.' },
    { icon:'🔍', use:'Resistance and continuity checks', why:'Testing fuses, wiring runs, motor windings, and individual components — the multimeter\'s primary strength.' },
    { icon:'📐', use:'Precise voltage across components', why:'Voltage across a specific resistor, diode forward drop, or supply rail — requires probes that a clamp can\'t place accurately.' },
    { icon:'📦', use:'Compact field kit', why:'Pocket-sized body makes the DMM ideal for control panels, PLCs, and instrumentation racks where space is limited.' },
  ].map(u => (
    <div class="flex gap-3 p-4 bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl">
      <span class="text-xl shrink-0">{u.icon}</span>
      <div>
        <p class="font-bold text-blue-900 text-sm">{u.use}</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-blue-800 mt-0.5">{u.why}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  ))}
</div>

<!-- ── WHEN CLAMP ── -->
<h2 id="choose-clamp">When to Choose a Clamp Meter</h2>

<div class="my-6 space-y-2">
  {[
    { icon:'⚡', use:'Live circuit load current', why:'No need to break the circuit or disconnect load. Clamp around one conductor and read instantly — the safest and fastest method.' },
    { icon:'🏭', use:'High current (> 20 A) applications', why:'Most multimeters max at 10–20 A. A clamp meter handles 400 A, 600 A, or 1000 A without modification or safety risk.' },
    { icon:'🔧', use:'Motor current measurement', why:'Check running current against nameplate rating; capture motor inrush/startup current with the peak hold function.' },
    { icon:'⚖️', use:'Three-phase load balancing', why:'Clamp each phase in turn to verify balance — without any circuit interruption or downtime.' },
    { icon:'🔎', use:'Electrical inspection / commissioning', why:'Rapidly survey current on every circuit in a distribution board or panel without any load interruption.' },
  ].map(u => (
    <div class="flex gap-3 p-4 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-xl">
      <span class="text-xl shrink-0">{u.icon}</span>
      <div>
        <p class="font-bold text-red-900 text-sm">{u.use}</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-red-800 mt-0.5">{u.why}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  ))}
</div>

<!-- ── CAN CLAMP REPLACE DMM ── -->
<h2 id="can-clamp-replace">Can a Clamp Meter Replace a Multimeter?</h2>

<p>Partially — but not completely. Most modern clamp meters include probe terminals and can measure voltage and resistance. However:</p>

<Callout type="warning" title="What a clamp meter can't do as well">
  <p>Low current below 1 A is unreliable. Resistance accuracy is typically 1% vs 0.1% on a quality DMM. Component testing (capacitance, diode, temperature) is absent on most clamp meters. CAT safety ratings on voltage inputs are sometimes lower than a dedicated DMM.</p>
</Callout>

<!-- ── WHICH FIRST ── -->
<h2 id="which-first">Which Should You Buy First?</h2>

<div class="my-8 grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-5">
  <div class="rounded-2xl border-2 border-blue-300 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="bg-blue-600 px-5 py-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-white font-bold text-lg">Buy Multimeter First</p>
      <p class="text-blue-200 text-xs mt-1">If you're an electronics or instrumentation engineer</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-5 bg-blue-50 space-y-2">
      {['Work primarily on control circuits and low-power equipment','Need precise voltage and resistance measurements','Test electronic components (diodes, capacitors)','Low current (mA range) measurements are common'].map(r => (
        <div class="flex gap-2 text-sm text-blue-900"><span class="text-blue-500 font-bold shrink-0">→</span>{r}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="rounded-2xl border-2 border-red-300 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="bg-[#E0252E] px-5 py-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-white font-bold text-lg">Buy Clamp Meter First</p>
      <p class="text-red-200 text-xs mt-1">If you're a field electrician or building services engineer</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-5 bg-red-50 space-y-2">
      {['Work on live distribution panels and motor control','Most measurements are load current checks','High current (> 20 A) applications are routine','Need inrush measurement for motor commissioning'].map(r => (
        <div class="flex gap-2 text-sm text-red-900"><span class="text-red-500 font-bold shrink-0">→</span>{r}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<Callout type="tip" title="The ideal toolkit: both">
  <p>A professional electrician or electrical engineer benefits from both. Use the multimeter for precision component and voltage work; use the clamp meter for non-invasive current measurement in live systems. CIE manufactures both — explore our <a href={u('/products/')}>complete product range</a> or <a href={u('/contact/')}>get in touch</a> and our team will recommend the right combination for your application.</p>
</Callout>
